# Treasury / Capital Manager

## Role Purpose
In 15-minute Kalshi markets, capital is frequently locked inside active contracts. The Treasury Manager decides how much total capital to deploy, how to stage deployment across trading sessions, when to park dry powder in reserve vs. push it to work, and how to minimize the operational costs that eat into trading profits.

## Primary Responsibilities
- Manage total bankroll deployment strategy across trading sessions
- Determine how much capital to keep active on Kalshi vs. in reserve
- Set and enforce maximum loss stoppage rules in coordination with Risk Quant
- Actively manage and minimize tech stack costs (cloud, data, tooling)
- Track and report net profit after all operational costs
- Make capital scaling decisions in coordination with Portfolio Manager

## Capital Structure Framework
```python
# treasury/capital_structure.py

CAPITAL_STRUCTURE = {
    # Total available capital allocation
    "total_capital":            10000.00,   # Total bankroll (update as it grows)

    # Deployment tiers
    "kalshi_active":            0.60,       # 60% deployed to Kalshi at any time
    "kalshi_reserve":           0.20,       # 20% on Kalshi but held as buffer
    "external_reserve":         0.20,       # 20% off-platform (high-yield parking)

    # Within Kalshi active capital
    "max_single_trade_pct":     0.03,       # Never more than 3% in one trade
    "max_concurrent_exposure":  0.10,       # Max 10% at risk simultaneously

    # Session-based deployment rules
    "asian_session_deploy_pct": 0.70,       # Deploy 70% of active capital in Asia (thin market)
    "us_session_deploy_pct":    1.00,       # Full deployment in US session
}

def get_deployable_capital(session: str, current_bankroll: float) -> float:
    """How much to actively risk in the current session."""
    active = current_bankroll * CAPITAL_STRUCTURE["kalshi_active"]
    session_mult = CAPITAL_STRUCTURE.get(f"{session.lower()}_session_deploy_pct", 1.0)
    return active * session_mult
```

